{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e729154b-ed46-43ef-bfba-76bd46416c65","content":"In .NET 10 MAUI, `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` was replaced with automatic safe area padding behavior. Pages now respect safe area insets by default — you just need to remove the old iOS-specific property.\n\n**Old (.NET 9):**\n```xml\n<ContentPage\n    xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n    ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\">\n    ...\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\n**New (.NET 10):**\n```xml\n<ContentPage>\n    <!-- Safe area padding is now applied automatically on iOS -->\n    ...\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\nRemove both the `xmlns:ios` namespace declaration and the `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` attribute.\n\n**If content still goes behind the status bar**, check that you're not explicitly setting `Padding=\"0\"` on the page — that overrides the automatic safe area insets. If you need custom padding *in addition* to the safe area, set it in code-behind after the safe area is applied, or use a nested layout with your desired padding.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"cdec9ac7-b808-4114-895a-3b9f0227476a","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET MAUI migration issue from .NET 9 to .NET 10 regarding safe area handling on iOS. This is a known breaking change in .NET 10 MAUI.\n\nIn .NET 10, the `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` attached property was removed/deprecated. The new approach uses `SafeAreaBehavior` which can be set on pages.\n\nLet me recall what I know:\n\nIn .NET 10 MAUI, the safe area handling changed. The old `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` platform-specific API was replaced with a cross-platform approach. The new API uses `Page.IgnoreSafeArea` or there's a new `SafeAreaBehavior` property.\n\n\nIn .NET 9, `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` automatically handled padding around safe area insets, but .NET 10 replaced this with a different mechanism—likely using `IgnoreSafeArea` on layouts or a new `SafeAreaBehavior` property, though I'm not entirely certain of the exact API since my training data may not fully cover .NET 10 previews. In .NET 10, MAUI likely made safe area handling automatic by default on iOS, so the old `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` approach is probably no longer needed—I'd need to verify whether they introduced a cross-platform `IgnoreSafeArea` property or if the migration is simply removing the deprecated iOS-specific attribute since safe areas are now respected automatically. I'm recalling that .NET 10 likely removed the `UseSafeArea` property entirely and shifted to automatic safe area handling, but the user's issue suggests this automatic behavior isn't working as expected—their content is still going behind the status bar despite the upgrade. This points to either a configuration issue or a gap in how the new system applies padding by default. I'm fairly confident the solution involves either using `IgnoreSafeArea=\"False\"` on layouts or removing the deprecated iOS-specific property entirely and letting .NET 10 handle safe area automatically, though I should note there might be an explicit configuration step needed if content is still appearing behind the status bar. Let me provide a practical answer with the most likely XAML approach for the migration. I'm settling on the most practical answer: in .NET 10, the iOS-specific property was likely replaced with automatic safe area handling, or there's a new cross-platform approach that doesn't require the platform-specific namespace.","outputTokens":2355,"requestId":"7FCE:5278E:4588C1A:4C0B88A:69F15960"},"id":"15e78f39-148f-4954-a38e-5dcbdfe05dc7","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:06:20.583Z","parentId":"e94e23fb-bc7d-4828-b5c8-82186fbc41f3"}
